{'text': 'ABSTRACT'}
{'text': 'Summary: The increasing size and complexity of biological'}
{'text': 'databases has led to a growing trend to federate rather than'}
{'text': 'duplicate them. In order to share data between federated databases,'}
{'text': 'protocols for the exchange mechanism must be developed. One'}
{'text': 'such data exchange protocol that is widely used is the Distributed'}
{'text': 'Annotation System (DAS). For example, DAS has enabled small'}
{'text': 'experimental groups to integrate their data into the Ensembl genome'}
{'text': 'browser. We have developed ProServer, a simple, lightweight, Perl-'}
{'text': 'based DAS server that does not depend on a separate HTTP server.'}
{'text': 'The ProServer package is easily extensible, allowing data to be'}
{'text': 'served from almost any underlying data model. Recent additions to'}
{'text': 'the DAS protocol have enabled both structure and alignment'}
{'text': '(sequence and structural) data to be exchanged. ProServer allows'}
{'text': 'both of these data types to be served.'}
{'text': 'Availability: ProServer can be downloaded from http://www.'}
{'text': 'sanger.ac.uk/proserver/ or CPAN http://search.cpan.org/\x18rpettett/.'}
{'text': 'Details on the system requirements and installation of ProServer can'}
{'text': 'be found at http://www.sanger.ac.uk/proserver/.'}
{'text': 'Contact: rmp@sanger.ac.uk'}
{'text': 'Supplementary Materials: DasClientExamples.pdf'}
{'text': ''}
{'text': '1 INTRODUCTION'}
{'text': ''}
{'text': 'High-throughput projects, such as the sequencing of the human'}
{'text': 'genome, have resulted in a deluge of data. Thus, a key challenge'}
{'text': 'in modern bioinformatics is to put in place mechanisms for'}
{'text': 'programmatic exchange of and access to large volumes of data'}
{'text': 'from disparate resources. As biological databases increase in'}
{'text': 'size and complexity, the classical mechanism of data exchange,'}
{'text': 'database duplication, can become impractical. For example,'}
{'text': 'the underlying database for Ensembl release 41 is over 700GB,'}
{'text': 'containing data on 25 different genomes,'}
{'text': 'spread across'}
{'text': 'hundreds of tables. An alternative to duplication of databases'}
{'text': 'is to interlink the distributed resources, termed federation.'}
{'text': 'However, for data exchange to take place between federated'}
{'text': 'databases, a mechanism and standardization of format must'}
{'text': 'be agreed. One such protocol for data exchange over a network'}
{'text': 'is the Distributed Annotation System (DAS).'}
{'text': ''}
{'text': 'Briefly, the DAS protocol standardizes queries and responses'}
{'text': 'for DNA or protein sequences, along with their annotations,'}
{'text': 'regardless of the underlying data architecture (Dowell et al.,'}
{'text': ''}
{'text': '*To whom correspondence should be addressed.'}
{'text': ''}
{'text': '2001). In common with other Web Services, client requests are'}
{'text': 'made via HTTP to servers which process them and return results'}
{'text': 'encapsulated in XML. Since the original DAS specification was'}
{'text': 'developed, DAS has been used extensively for the annotation of'}
{'text': 'genome (DNA) sequences and, more recently, of proteins.'}
{'text': 'In addition, many extensions to the DAS protocol have been'}
{'text': 'proposed. Two of these extensions, developed over the past'}
{'text': 'year, allow the exchange of sequence alignments and protein'}
{'text': 'structure data. These extensions enable annotations to be'}
{'text': 'integrated across DNA, protein sequence and protein structure.'}
{'text': 'We have developed ProServer, a simple, user-friendly'}
{'text': ''}
{'text': 'package for making data available using the DAS protocol.'}
{'text': ''}
{'text': '2 PROSERVER'}
{'text': ''}
{'text': 'ProServer has been available from the Wellcome Trust Sanger'}
{'text': 'Institute since 2003. We have recently added additional function-'}
{'text': 'ality and documentation to improve usability and robustness.'}
{'text': ''}
{'text': '2.1 Architecture and flexibility'}
{'text': ''}
{'text': 'ProServer is a standalone, lightweight DAS server, written in'}
{'text': 'Perl and designed to have low system requirements. The'}
{'text': 'architecture of ProServer is represented in Figure 1. At the top'}
{'text': 'level, there is a daemon executable which acts as a broker'}
{'text': 'between requests and the code that will handle them. The server'}
{'text': 'is configured using a ‘.ini’-format configuration file holding'}
{'text': 'settings for data sources provided by the server (Fig. 1).'}
{'text': 'The networking requirements of ProServer are handled by'}
{'text': 'the POE package (http://poe.perl.org/), which implements'}
{'text': 'a portable multitasking and networking framework for Perl.'}
{'text': ''}
{'text': 'The server sits upon a number of source adaptors with each'}
{'text': 'one dedicated to a single underlying data store. Incoming'}
{'text': 'queries are passed from the daemon to the appropriate source'}
{'text': 'adaptor. The source adaptors handle access to the data store'}
{'text': 'and the conversion of queries into generic DAS response data'}
{'text': 'structures. Linking source adaptors to their data stores are'}
{'text': 'generic transport helpers which are responsible for handling'}
{'text': 'data acquisition (Fig. 1).'}
{'text': ''}
{'text': 'Depending on the format of any new data set, it may be'}
{'text': 'necessary to implement a new transport helper (Fig. 1).'}
{'text': 'However, ProServer comes bundled with helpers for some'}
{'text': 'common data stores, for example: flatfile, GFF. MySQL,'}
{'text': 'Oracle and SRS getz. These transport helpers are all simple,'}
{'text': 'command-line or socket-handling modules.'}
{'text': ''}
