{'text': '\x0cA simple, extensible Perl DAS server'}
{'text': ''}
{'text': 'computation. Thus, providing the underlying data store is'}
{'text': 'organized optimally (as it would need to be with the alternative'}
{'text': 'servers), then similar performance and scalability should be'}
{'text': 'achievable regardless of the DAS server used.'}
{'text': ''}
{'text': 'The simplicity of ProServer means that it can be deployed'}
{'text': 'by users with only basic bioinformatics skills. Therefore,'}
{'text': 'groups can expose their data set, whether large or small,'}
{'text': 'to the scientific community with little additional overhead to'}
{'text': 'the storage of the data set.'}
{'text': ''}
{'text': '2.3 Examples'}
{'text': ''}
{'text': 'ProServer was originally developed in conjunction with the'}
{'text': 'Ensembl project (Birney et al., 2006), to display features such as'}
{'text': 'gene predictions on chromosomes. Since the original release'}
{'text': 'of ProServer, with only features and sequence capabilities,'}
{'text': 'we have added both alignment and structure functionality.'}
{'text': 'This has enabled the Pfam database (Finn et al., 2006)'}
{'text': 'to provide access to their protein sequence alignments using'}
{'text': 'ProServer to serve data directly from the underlying MySQL'}
{'text': 'database (see http://das.sanger.ac.uk/das/pfamAlign).'}
{'text': ''}
{'text': 'Other projects outside of'}
{'text': ''}
{'text': 'the Wellcome Trust Sanger'}
{'text': 'Institute are already using ProServer for the exchange of'}
{'text': 'feature annotations: examples include Gene3D (Yeast et al.,'}
{'text': '2006), CBS (O´ lason, 2005) and AnoEST (Kriventseva et al.,'}
{'text': '2005).'}
{'text': ''}
{'text': 'The supplementary materials contain a list of some of the'}
{'text': 'most popular clients that provide an insight to the use of DAS'}
{'text': 'within the scientific community.'}
{'text': ''}
{'text': '3 CONCLUSIONS'}
{'text': ''}
{'text': 'The federation of databases removes the effort'}
{'text': 'involved'}
{'text': 'with their duplication and maintenance and the problem of'}
{'text': 'asynchronous versions. The relatively simple architecture'}
{'text': 'of ProServer means that even small groups can make their'}
{'text': 'data available via DAS, even if it is stored only as a flatfile,'}
{'text': 'without the overheads of running a web server. Once available,'}
{'text': 'this resource can be readily integrated into other data sets.'}
{'text': 'For example, the Ensembl browser (Birney et al., 2006) allows'}
{'text': 'new DAS sources to be added and displayed alongside existing'}
{'text': 'annotation, even if they are only internally available at an'}
{'text': 'institute. Rare chromosomal abnormality data from the'}
{'text': 'DECIPHER project (http://decipher.sanger.ac.uk/syndromes)'}
{'text': 'are being displayed in a genomic context via the Ensembl'}
{'text': 'browser using ProServer, for example, the 1p36 microdeletion'}
{'text': '(http://www.sanger.ac.uk/turl/72d).'}
{'text': ''}
{'text': 'A survey of the DAS registry (Prlic et al., 2006) (http://'}
{'text': 'www.dasregistry.org/) demonstrated that 69 of'}
{'text': 'the 103'}
{'text': 'registered feature servers were using ProServer at the time of'}
{'text': 'writing. Thus, ProServer is already being widely used to provide'}
{'text': 'data via the DAS protocol. The recent extensions increase'}
{'text': 'the range of data types available via DAS, allowing the transfer'}
{'text': 'of annotations between aligned objects. These extensions'}
{'text': 'are leading to the development of exciting new clients that'}
{'text': 'bring together different data types (Prlic A et al., 2005).'}
{'text': 'ProServer’s minimal requirements and simplicity,'}
{'text': 'together'}
{'text': 'with the widespread use of DAS in bioinformatics makes'}
{'text': 'ProServer a valuable tool for publishing data in a common,'}
{'text': 'standard'}
{'text': 'programmatic'}
{'text': ''}
{'text': 'format. The'}
